@alan white The term "holocaust denier" describes a group of people who deny something that is plainly true. The term "climate change denier" is apt because it also describes a group of people who deny something that is plainly true.

The suffix "denier" is used in the pejorative because people who deny things which are plainly true necessarily invite ridicule. Individuals who insist that Elvis Presley is still alive are ridiculed, because that belief denies a something that's plainly true, i.e., that Elvis Presley is deceased. Denying the holocaust is like this. Denying anthropogenic climate change is like this. It is denying something that is plainly true.

Climate change deniers are not referred to as "skeptics" by anybody other than themselves because they are plainly out of touch with reality. Skeptical people are not necessarily out of touch with reality, but climate deniers definitely are. We know this is true because the evidence indicates that the climate is changing, and that anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions are the primary cause.

